/* CompTIA AI Fundamentals :: content/quiz1.js — question bank for Domain 1 (100 items). */
window.AIFUND = window.AIFUND || {}; AIFUND.questions = AIFUND.questions || [];
AIFUND.questions.push(
{ id:"D1-001", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"easy", q:"Your email app automatically suggests a short reply like \"Sounds good, thanks!\" when you open a message. This helpful feature is an everyday example of:", options:["Artificial intelligence built into a common tool","A manual macro you recorded yourself","A spreadsheet formula you typed in","A printer driver update"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Artificial intelligence built into a common tool</strong> is correct because smart-reply suggestions are generated by an AI model that predicts likely responses from the message content, and this is one of the most common places people encounter AI without realizing it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A manual macro you recorded yourself</b>: a recorded macro replays fixed steps you defined, whereas smart replies are generated fresh for each new email.</span><span class='qd'><b>A spreadsheet formula you typed in</b>: a formula only calculates values in cells and cannot compose natural-language reply suggestions.</span><span class='qd'><b>A printer driver update</b>: a driver update simply lets your computer talk to a printer and has nothing to do with generating text.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-002", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"easy", q:"A coworker says, \"I use AI every day but I'm not a programmer.\" Which everyday activity BEST supports that statement?", options:["Manually alphabetizing a printed list","Asking a voice assistant to set a timer while cooking","Stapling a report together","Turning a light switch on and off"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Asking a voice assistant to set a timer while cooking</strong> is correct because voice assistants use AI to understand spoken language and act on it, so a non-programmer genuinely uses AI just by talking to the assistant.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Manually alphabetizing a printed list</b>: sorting paper by hand is a manual task with no software or AI involved.</span><span class='qd'><b>Stapling a report together</b>: stapling is a physical action and involves no computing at all.</span><span class='qd'><b>Turning a light switch on and off</b>: a basic switch simply completes a circuit and has no intelligence behind it.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-003", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"easy", q:"Which of these is a common example of AI already working behind the scenes in tools many people use daily?", options:["A paper calendar on the wall","A wired doorbell that only rings","Streaming services recommending shows based on what you watched","A manual can opener"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Streaming services recommending shows based on what you watched</strong> is correct because recommendation engines use AI to learn your preferences and predict what you might enjoy next, a very familiar everyday use of AI.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A paper calendar on the wall</b>: a paper calendar is a static object that cannot learn or recommend anything.</span><span class='qd'><b>A wired doorbell that only rings</b>: a simple doorbell just makes a sound and performs no analysis.</span><span class='qd'><b>A manual can opener</b>: a can opener is a mechanical tool with no software or intelligence.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-004", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"easy", q:"A teacher wants to save time by generating a first draft of a quiz on a topic. Which modern tool is designed to help with this kind of drafting task?", options:["A calculator app","A file compression utility","A screen brightness slider","A generative AI chat assistant like ChatGPT"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>A generative AI chat assistant like ChatGPT</strong> is correct because generative AI assistants can produce first drafts of text such as quiz questions from a simple request, which directly matches the drafting need.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A calculator app</b>: a calculator only performs arithmetic and cannot write quiz questions.</span><span class='qd'><b>A file compression utility</b>: compression shrinks file size and produces no new content.</span><span class='qd'><b>A screen brightness slider</b>: a brightness control adjusts the display and has nothing to do with creating content.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-005", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"A small-business owner with no technical staff wants to draft social media posts faster. Which approach reflects a realistic, practical use of AI in the workplace today?", options:["Using a widely available AI writing assistant to generate post drafts they then edit","Hiring a data science team to build a custom model from scratch","Waiting until AI is regulated before using any tool","Assuming AI cannot help with marketing tasks"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Using a widely available AI writing assistant to generate post drafts they then edit</strong> is correct because everyday AI tools let non-technical people produce drafts quickly and refine them, which is exactly how most workplaces adopt AI today.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Hiring a data science team to build a custom model from scratch</b>: building a custom model is far too costly and unnecessary for simple drafting when ready-made tools exist.</span><span class='qd'><b>Waiting until AI is regulated before using any tool</b>: refusing to use available tools offers no benefit and misunderstands that many are already safe to use for drafting.</span><span class='qd'><b>Assuming AI cannot help with marketing tasks</b>: AI writing assistants are in fact widely used for marketing content, so the assumption is false.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-006", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"Which statement BEST describes how AI is showing up in ordinary workplace software?", options:["It is limited to research labs and never touches office tools","It is increasingly embedded as features inside familiar apps like email, documents, and chat","It only exists as separate hardware you must buy","It requires every employee to learn programming first"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>It is increasingly embedded as features inside familiar apps like email, documents, and chat</strong> is correct because vendors are adding AI features such as summarization, drafting, and suggestions directly into everyday productivity apps that workers already use.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It is limited to research labs and never touches office tools</b>: AI has clearly moved beyond labs and is now built into mainstream office software.</span><span class='qd'><b>It only exists as separate hardware you must buy</b>: most workplace AI arrives as software features, not as dedicated hardware.</span><span class='qd'><b>It requires every employee to learn programming first</b>: these embedded features are designed for ordinary users and require no programming.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-007", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"A customer types a question into a company website and a chat window answers instantly at 2 a.m. without a human agent. This is MOST likely an example of:", options:["A human employee working overnight for every customer","A printed FAQ brochure","An AI-powered chatbot handling common questions","A phone left off the hook"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>An AI-powered chatbot handling common questions</strong> is correct because automated chat that responds instantly at any hour without a human is a classic AI chatbot use case for customer service.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A human employee working overnight for every customer</b>: an instant response for every visitor around the clock is not how a single human agent works, which is why automation is used.</span><span class='qd'><b>A printed FAQ brochure</b>: a brochure is static paper and cannot respond to a typed question in a chat window.</span><span class='qd'><b>A phone left off the hook</b>: an off-hook phone provides no answers and is unrelated to a website chat.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-008", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"An HR manager wants AI to help summarize long policy documents for staff. Which is the MOST appropriate everyday use of AI here?", options:["Letting AI make final hiring and firing decisions with no oversight","Replacing the entire HR department with a chatbot overnight","Refusing to use AI because summaries are impossible","Using AI to draft plain-language summaries that a person reviews for accuracy"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Using AI to draft plain-language summaries that a person reviews for accuracy</strong> is correct because summarizing long documents is a strong, practical use of AI, and keeping a human reviewer ensures the summary is trustworthy.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Letting AI make final hiring and firing decisions with no oversight</b>: high-stakes personnel decisions should not be automated without human judgment and accountability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Replacing the entire HR department with a chatbot overnight</b>: AI assists with tasks but cannot responsibly replace an entire function all at once.</span><span class='qd'><b>Refusing to use AI because summaries are impossible</b>: summarizing text is one of the things AI does well, so the refusal is based on a false premise.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-009", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"hard", q:"A nurse manager is considering AI tools for the clinic. Which use is the MOST appropriate first step given that AI can make mistakes?", options:["Using AI to draft appointment reminder messages that staff approve before sending","Letting AI diagnose patients and prescribe medication automatically","Having AI silently alter patient records without review","Trusting AI output as always correct because it sounds confident"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Using AI to draft appointment reminder messages that staff approve before sending</strong> is correct because it is a low-risk task where a human reviews the output, which is the responsible way to introduce AI where errors could occur.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Letting AI diagnose patients and prescribe medication automatically</b>: unsupervised diagnosis and prescribing is high-risk and unsafe for an early, unmonitored AI use.</span><span class='qd'><b>Having AI silently alter patient records without review</b>: changing records without human review removes accountability and can introduce dangerous errors.</span><span class='qd'><b>Trusting AI output as always correct because it sounds confident</b>: confident-sounding output can still be wrong, so blind trust is unsafe.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-010", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"hard", q:"An accountant notices new \"AI assist\" buttons appearing in the spreadsheet and email software the firm already licenses. What is the BEST way to think about this trend?", options:["AI features only matter to the IT department and no one else","AI is becoming a built-in feature layer across tools staff already use, so basic AI literacy is now broadly useful","These buttons are decorative and perform no real function","Adopting any AI feature requires replacing all existing software"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>AI is becoming a built-in feature layer across tools staff already use, so basic AI literacy is now broadly useful</strong> is correct because AI is increasingly woven into mainstream apps, making general familiarity valuable for workers in any role, not just specialists.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>AI features only matter to the IT department and no one else</b>: these features assist everyday tasks for all staff, not just IT.</span><span class='qd'><b>These buttons are decorative and perform no real function</b>: the AI assist features perform real tasks like drafting and summarizing, so they are not decorative.</span><span class='qd'><b>Adopting any AI feature requires replacing all existing software</b>: the features are added inside existing apps, so no wholesale replacement is needed.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-011", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"easy", q:"When your phone's photo app groups pictures by faces or lets you search \"beach,\" which technology is doing that work?", options:["A basic flashlight function","The phone's ringtone settings","AI-based image recognition","A paper photo album"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>AI-based image recognition</strong> is correct because grouping photos by face and searching by content require an AI model that recognizes what is in the images.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A basic flashlight function</b>: the flashlight only turns the camera light on and cannot analyze photo content.</span><span class='qd'><b>The phone's ringtone settings</b>: ringtone settings control sounds and have nothing to do with recognizing images.</span><span class='qd'><b>A paper photo album</b>: a physical album cannot search or sort photos by what they contain.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-012", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"A manager asks whether using AI at work always requires expensive specialists. What is the MOST accurate response for a non-technical team?", options:["Yes, only PhD data scientists can ever use AI","AI can only be used by writing computer code","AI must be installed on a supercomputer to function","No, many practical AI tools are designed for everyday users through simple chat or menu options"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>No, many practical AI tools are designed for everyday users through simple chat or menu options</strong> is correct because a large share of modern AI tools are built for non-technical people to use through plain language or point-and-click features.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Yes, only PhD data scientists can ever use AI</b>: everyday assistants are made for general users, so advanced degrees are not required to use them.</span><span class='qd'><b>AI can only be used by writing computer code</b>: chat-based assistants let people use AI with plain language and no coding.</span><span class='qd'><b>AI must be installed on a supercomputer to function</b>: most consumer AI runs in the cloud and is accessed from ordinary devices.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-013", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"Which pairing correctly matches an everyday task with an AI capability that commonly assists it?", options:["Translating a menu while traveling — AI language translation","Physically ironing a shirt — AI translation","Sharpening a pencil — machine learning recommendations","Watering a plant — image generation"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Translating a menu while traveling — AI language translation</strong> is correct because translation apps use AI to convert text or speech between languages, which directly helps a traveler read a foreign menu.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Physically ironing a shirt — AI translation</b>: ironing is a manual chore and language translation cannot press clothing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Sharpening a pencil — machine learning recommendations</b>: sharpening a pencil is mechanical and unrelated to recommendation systems.</span><span class='qd'><b>Watering a plant — image generation</b>: watering a plant is a physical act that image generation has nothing to do with.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-014", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"hard", q:"A department wants a quick win with AI that improves productivity while keeping risk low. Which choice BEST fits that goal?", options:["Automating all financial approvals through AI with no human check","Using an AI assistant to summarize meeting notes, with staff verifying key action items","Publishing AI-written content externally without any review","Letting AI send legal contracts on the company's behalf unsupervised"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Using an AI assistant to summarize meeting notes, with staff verifying key action items</strong> is correct because note summarization is high-value and low-risk, and verifying key items keeps humans accountable for accuracy.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Automating all financial approvals through AI with no human check</b>: unchecked automation of money decisions is high-risk and invites costly errors.</span><span class='qd'><b>Publishing AI-written content externally without any review</b>: releasing unreviewed AI text can spread mistakes and damage credibility.</span><span class='qd'><b>Letting AI send legal contracts on the company's behalf unsupervised</b>: sending binding contracts without oversight is legally risky and inappropriate.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-015", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"easy", q:"A GPS navigation app that reroutes you around a traffic jam in real time is using AI mainly to:", options:["Charge your phone battery","Print paper maps for you","Predict and choose faster routes from live traffic data","Change your car's oil"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Predict and choose faster routes from live traffic data</strong> is correct because navigation apps use AI to analyze current conditions and recommend the quickest path, adjusting as traffic changes.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Charge your phone battery</b>: routing has nothing to do with powering the device.</span><span class='qd'><b>Print paper maps for you</b>: the app displays digital directions and does not produce printed maps.</span><span class='qd'><b>Change your car's oil</b>: vehicle maintenance is a physical task unrelated to navigation software.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-016", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"Which of the following is the BEST example of AI helping with an everyday customer-service workflow?", options:["A stapler organizing paperwork","A whiteboard marker writing on its own","A filing cabinet sorting tickets by importance","An assistant drafting a polite response to a complaint for an agent to review and send"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>An assistant drafting a polite response to a complaint for an agent to review and send</strong> is correct because generating suggested replies that a human approves is a common and practical AI aid in customer service.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A stapler organizing paperwork</b>: a stapler only fastens pages and cannot draft responses.</span><span class='qd'><b>A whiteboard marker writing on its own</b>: a marker has no capability to compose or organize anything.</span><span class='qd'><b>A filing cabinet sorting tickets by importance</b>: a cabinet is passive storage and cannot evaluate or prioritize tickets.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-017", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"hard", q:"An office is excited about AI but worried about mistakes. Which principle should guide how they roll it out across everyday tasks?", options:["Start with low-stakes tasks and keep a human reviewing AI output","Remove all human review to move faster","Apply AI first to the most sensitive legal and medical decisions","Trust AI completely because it never makes errors"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Start with low-stakes tasks and keep a human reviewing AI output</strong> is correct because piloting AI on lower-risk work with human oversight lets an organization gain value while catching errors before they cause harm.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Remove all human review to move faster</b>: removing review eliminates the safety net that catches AI mistakes.</span><span class='qd'><b>Apply AI first to the most sensitive legal and medical decisions</b>: beginning with the highest-stakes decisions maximizes potential harm from any error.</span><span class='qd'><b>Trust AI completely because it never makes errors</b>: AI can and does make mistakes, so complete trust is unwarranted.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-018", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"easy", q:"Spam filters that automatically move junk email to a separate folder are a long-standing everyday example of:", options:["A manual sorting rule you must run each morning","AI/machine learning classifying messages","A hardware firewall on your desk","A screen saver"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>AI/machine learning classifying messages</strong> is correct because modern spam filters use learned patterns to decide which messages are junk, a familiar AI application that works automatically.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A manual sorting rule you must run each morning</b>: spam filtering happens automatically and continuously, not as a manual daily task.</span><span class='qd'><b>A hardware firewall on your desk</b>: a firewall controls network traffic and is not what sorts email into a junk folder.</span><span class='qd'><b>A screen saver</b>: a screen saver only displays graphics when idle and does not classify email.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-019", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"A librarian wants to offer patrons help finding books using natural questions like \"something like a cozy mystery.\" Which technology best enables that experience?", options:["A barcode scanner alone","A card catalog drawer","An AI system that understands the meaning of the request and suggests matches","A book return slot"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>An AI system that understands the meaning of the request and suggests matches</strong> is correct because interpreting a natural, fuzzy request and recommending similar items is exactly what AI language and recommendation systems do.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A barcode scanner alone</b>: a scanner only reads a code from a known book and cannot interpret a descriptive request.</span><span class='qd'><b>A card catalog drawer</b>: a physical catalog requires exact lookups and cannot understand a casual description.</span><span class='qd'><b>A book return slot</b>: a return slot simply accepts returned books and offers no search help.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-020", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"Which statement about AI in everyday tools is MOST accurate for a general workplace audience?", options:["AI features are perfect and never require oversight","AI features are only marketing hype with no real use","AI features can only be used by IT professionals","AI features can boost productivity but still need human judgment for important decisions"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>AI features can boost productivity but still need human judgment for important decisions</strong> is correct because AI genuinely helps with many tasks while its output must be checked by people, especially when decisions matter.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>AI features are perfect and never require oversight</b>: AI can make errors, so oversight remains necessary.</span><span class='qd'><b>AI features are only marketing hype with no real use</b>: AI features provide real, measurable help in many everyday tasks.</span><span class='qd'><b>AI features can only be used by IT professionals</b>: many AI features are built for all employees, not just IT staff.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-021", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"easy", q:"Which definition BEST describes artificial intelligence (AI) in plain terms?", options:["Computer systems that perform tasks that normally require human intelligence","A brand of laptop hardware","Any software that has a colorful interface","The internet cable that connects your home"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Computer systems that perform tasks that normally require human intelligence</strong> is correct because AI broadly refers to machines carrying out tasks like understanding language, recognizing images, or making decisions that we associate with human thinking.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A brand of laptop hardware</b>: AI is a field of capability, not a specific hardware brand.</span><span class='qd'><b>Any software that has a colorful interface</b>: a colorful interface says nothing about whether a program is intelligent.</span><span class='qd'><b>The internet cable that connects your home</b>: a cable is physical connectivity and is unrelated to intelligent behavior.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-022", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"easy", q:"Machine learning (ML) is BEST described as:", options:["A way to physically build robots","A type of AI where systems learn patterns from data instead of following only hand-written rules","A method for printing documents faster","A tool only for editing photos"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>A type of AI where systems learn patterns from data instead of following only hand-written rules</strong> is correct because machine learning is the subset of AI in which a system improves at a task by finding patterns in examples rather than being explicitly programmed for every case.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A way to physically build robots</b>: building robot hardware is engineering, not the learning-from-data concept of ML.</span><span class='qd'><b>A method for printing documents faster</b>: printing speed is unrelated to learning from data.</span><span class='qd'><b>A tool only for editing photos</b>: ML has many uses far beyond photo editing, so this is far too narrow.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-023", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"easy", q:"Generative AI is BEST defined as AI that:", options:["Only deletes files to save space","Merely counts how many words are in a document","Creates new content such as text, images, or audio","Can only answer yes or no questions"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Creates new content such as text, images, or audio</strong> is correct because generative AI is specifically the kind of AI that produces new outputs like written passages, pictures, or sound based on what it learned.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Only deletes files to save space</b>: deleting files is a storage task and the opposite of generating new content.</span><span class='qd'><b>Merely counts how many words are in a document</b>: counting words is a simple utility function, not content creation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Can only answer yes or no questions</b>: generative AI produces rich, varied content and is not limited to yes-or-no answers.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-024", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"medium", q:"How do AI, machine learning, and generative AI relate to one another?", options:["They are three completely unrelated fields","Generative AI is the broadest, and AI is a small part of it","They all mean exactly the same thing","Machine learning is a subset of AI, and generative AI is a subset of machine learning"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Machine learning is a subset of AI, and generative AI is a subset of machine learning</strong> is correct because AI is the broad umbrella, machine learning sits inside it, and generative AI is a further specialization within machine learning.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>They are three completely unrelated fields</b>: they are nested concepts, so they are closely related, not unrelated.</span><span class='qd'><b>Generative AI is the broadest, and AI is a small part of it</b>: this reverses the hierarchy; AI is the broadest term.</span><span class='qd'><b>They all mean exactly the same thing</b>: each term has a distinct scope, so they are not identical.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-025", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"medium", q:"A retailer builds a system that studies past sales to predict which products will sell out next month. This is BEST described as:", options:["Machine learning making predictions from historical data","Generative AI writing a novel","A simple printed sales receipt","A manual inventory count with no software"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Machine learning making predictions from historical data</strong> is correct because learning patterns from past sales to forecast future demand is a classic predictive machine learning task.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Generative AI writing a novel</b>: generating creative prose is unrelated to forecasting product demand.</span><span class='qd'><b>A simple printed sales receipt</b>: a receipt records a single transaction and makes no predictions.</span><span class='qd'><b>A manual inventory count with no software</b>: counting stock by hand does not analyze data to predict future sales.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-026", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"medium", q:"Which task is the BEST example of generative AI rather than traditional predictive AI?", options:["Flagging a transaction as likely fraud","Writing an original poem about autumn on request","Sorting emails into spam or not spam","Estimating tomorrow's temperature from weather data"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Writing an original poem about autumn on request</strong> is correct because producing brand-new creative text is generative AI, whereas the other tasks classify or predict from existing data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Flagging a transaction as likely fraud</b>: fraud flagging is a predictive classification task, not content generation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Sorting emails into spam or not spam</b>: spam sorting categorizes existing messages rather than creating new content.</span><span class='qd'><b>Estimating tomorrow's temperature from weather data</b>: forecasting a number from data is prediction, not generation.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-027", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"medium", q:"Which of the following is TRUE about generative AI?", options:["It always produces perfectly factual answers","It cannot create images, only text","It can produce content that looks new but may sometimes be inaccurate","It stores an exact copy of the internet to look up answers"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>It can produce content that looks new but may sometimes be inaccurate</strong> is correct because generative AI creates fluent, novel-looking output that can nonetheless contain factual errors, so results should be verified.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It always produces perfectly factual answers</b>: generative AI can produce confident but incorrect statements, so it is not always factual.</span><span class='qd'><b>It cannot create images, only text</b>: generative AI can create images, audio, and more, not just text.</span><span class='qd'><b>It stores an exact copy of the internet to look up answers</b>: it generates output from learned patterns rather than looking up a stored copy of the internet.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-028", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"hard", q:"A colleague says, \"All AI is generative AI.\" What is the BEST correction?", options:["That is correct because every AI creates new text","Generative AI and AI are unrelated terms","AI is a subset of generative AI","Generative AI is only one type of AI; much AI classifies, predicts, or recommends without generating new content"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Generative AI is only one type of AI; much AI classifies, predicts, or recommends without generating new content</strong> is correct because AI includes many non-generative tasks such as filtering spam or forecasting demand, so equating all AI with generative AI is inaccurate.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>That is correct because every AI creates new text</b>: many AI systems classify or predict and never create text, so the claim is false.</span><span class='qd'><b>Generative AI and AI are unrelated terms</b>: generative AI is a part of AI, so they are related, not unrelated.</span><span class='qd'><b>AI is a subset of generative AI</b>: this reverses the relationship, since generative AI is the subset of AI.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-029", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"hard", q:"An analyst must classify whether a system that recommends movies based on viewing history is generative AI. What is the MOST accurate classification?", options:["It is typically a predictive/recommendation system, not generative AI, because it ranks existing items rather than creating new content","It is generative AI because it produces a list","It is not AI at all","It is generative AI because it uses a computer"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>It is typically a predictive/recommendation system, not generative AI, because it ranks existing items rather than creating new content</strong> is correct because a recommender selects and orders items that already exist rather than generating original content, which is the defining line for generative AI.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It is generative AI because it produces a list</b>: producing a ranked list of existing movies is not generating new content.</span><span class='qd'><b>It is not AI at all</b>: recommendation engines are a well-established form of AI, so this is incorrect.</span><span class='qd'><b>It is generative AI because it uses a computer</b>: using a computer does not make something generative AI; the defining factor is creating new content.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-030", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"easy", q:"Which everyday example BEST illustrates \"machine learning\" as opposed to a fixed rule?", options:["A light that turns on only when a switch is flipped","A music app that improves its song suggestions the more you listen","A door that opens only with a specific physical key","A clock that shows the same time format every day"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>A music app that improves its song suggestions the more you listen</strong> is correct because getting better from experience and data is the hallmark of machine learning, unlike a fixed rule that never changes.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A light that turns on only when a switch is flipped</b>: a switch follows one fixed rule and never learns.</span><span class='qd'><b>A door that opens only with a specific physical key</b>: a keyed lock is a fixed mechanism with no learning.</span><span class='qd'><b>A clock that shows the same time format every day</b>: displaying a constant format involves no learning from data.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-031", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"medium", q:"Which statement correctly distinguishes AI from machine learning?", options:["ML is broader than AI and contains it","AI and ML are identical with no difference","AI is the broad goal of intelligent behavior; ML is one approach that learns from data","AI only refers to robots while ML refers to websites"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>AI is the broad goal of intelligent behavior; ML is one approach that learns from data</strong> is correct because AI is the overarching aim of building intelligent systems, and machine learning is a specific data-driven method for achieving it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>ML is broader than AI and contains it</b>: this inverts the relationship, as AI is the broader concept.</span><span class='qd'><b>AI and ML are identical with no difference</b>: ML is a subset of AI, so they are not identical.</span><span class='qd'><b>AI only refers to robots while ML refers to websites</b>: neither term is limited to robots or websites; both are far broader.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-032", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"hard", q:"A team wants a one-sentence explanation for executives about why generative AI feels different from older software. Which is BEST?", options:["Generative AI is just a faster calculator","Generative AI only runs pre-written scripts word for word","Generative AI stores answers in a spreadsheet and reads them back","Unlike traditional software that follows fixed instructions, generative AI produces flexible, original-looking content from patterns it learned"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Unlike traditional software that follows fixed instructions, generative AI produces flexible, original-looking content from patterns it learned</strong> is correct because it captures the key difference: generative AI creates adaptable new output rather than executing rigid, predefined steps.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Generative AI is just a faster calculator</b>: a calculator computes fixed math and cannot create varied content.</span><span class='qd'><b>Generative AI only runs pre-written scripts word for word</b>: generative AI does not replay fixed scripts; it generates novel responses.</span><span class='qd'><b>Generative AI stores answers in a spreadsheet and reads them back</b>: it generates responses from learned patterns rather than reading stored answers from a sheet.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-033", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"medium", q:"Which of these is the clearest example of a generative AI output?", options:["A drafted email written from a one-line prompt","A yes/no fraud flag on a payment","A calculated total in a budget cell","A sorted list of files by date"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>A drafted email written from a one-line prompt</strong> is correct because composing new written text from a short request is generative AI, while the other options classify, calculate, or sort existing data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A yes/no fraud flag on a payment</b>: a fraud flag is a classification decision, not created content.</span><span class='qd'><b>A calculated total in a budget cell</b>: a total is arithmetic on existing numbers, not generation.</span><span class='qd'><b>A sorted list of files by date</b>: sorting rearranges existing items and creates no new content.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-034", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"hard", q:"An instructor wants students to see that \"AI\" is an umbrella term. Which grouping is arranged from BROADEST to most specific correctly?", options:["Generative AI, then machine learning, then artificial intelligence","Artificial intelligence, then machine learning, then generative AI","Machine learning, then artificial intelligence, then generative AI","Generative AI, then artificial intelligence, then machine learning"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Artificial intelligence, then machine learning, then generative AI</strong> is correct because AI is the widest field, machine learning is a subset of AI, and generative AI is a further subset of machine learning.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Generative AI, then machine learning, then artificial intelligence</b>: this lists them from narrowest to broadest, the reverse of what was asked.</span><span class='qd'><b>Machine learning, then artificial intelligence, then generative AI</b>: this misplaces AI in the middle when it is actually the broadest.</span><span class='qd'><b>Generative AI, then artificial intelligence, then machine learning</b>: this ordering scrambles the true nesting of the three terms.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-035", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"easy", q:"When people say a chatbot uses a \"large language model,\" the model's core job is to:", options:["Physically store your files in a cabinet","Scan documents with a camera","Predict and produce likely text based on the words it is given","Replace your keyboard hardware"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Predict and produce likely text based on the words it is given</strong> is correct because a large language model generates responses by predicting the most plausible next words given the input, which is how chatbots form replies.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Physically store your files in a cabinet</b>: a language model produces text and does not physically store files.</span><span class='qd'><b>Scan documents with a camera</b>: scanning is an image-capture task, not language prediction.</span><span class='qd'><b>Replace your keyboard hardware</b>: a model is software and does not replace physical hardware.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-036", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"easy", q:"When you type a question into a chatbot like ChatGPT, the text you enter is called the:", options:["Firewall","Spreadsheet","Router","Prompt"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Prompt</strong> is correct because the prompt is the input text or instruction you give the AI, which it uses to generate a response.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Firewall</b>: a firewall filters network traffic and is unrelated to the text you type to an AI.</span><span class='qd'><b>Spreadsheet</b>: a spreadsheet organizes data in cells and is not the input to a chatbot.</span><span class='qd'><b>Router</b>: a router directs network traffic and has nothing to do with an AI request.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-037", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"easy", q:"At a conceptual level, how does a generative AI chatbot most often build its answer?", options:["By predicting likely words one after another based on patterns it learned","By copying a single stored answer word for word","By calling a human to type the reply live","By randomly guessing letters with no pattern"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>By predicting likely words one after another based on patterns it learned</strong> is correct because generative text models assemble responses by repeatedly choosing plausible next words, forming coherent sentences from learned language patterns.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>By copying a single stored answer word for word</b>: the model generates fresh text rather than retrieving one fixed stored answer.</span><span class='qd'><b>By calling a human to type the reply live</b>: no human is typing; the model produces the text itself.</span><span class='qd'><b>By randomly guessing letters with no pattern</b>: the output follows learned patterns, not random letter guessing.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-038", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"Why can a generative AI tool give a confident-sounding answer that is actually wrong?", options:["It always double-checks a certified encyclopedia first","It predicts plausible-sounding text and does not truly verify facts","It refuses to answer unless it is certain","It only repeats officially approved statements"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>It predicts plausible-sounding text and does not truly verify facts</strong> is correct because the model aims to produce likely, fluent language, which can read as confident even when the underlying claim is incorrect.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It always double-checks a certified encyclopedia first</b>: a generative model does not inherently verify each claim against an authoritative source.</span><span class='qd'><b>It refuses to answer unless it is certain</b>: models often answer even when uncertain, which is why errors slip through.</span><span class='qd'><b>It only repeats officially approved statements</b>: the model generates new phrasing rather than repeating only approved statements.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-039", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"A generative AI produces a made-up citation that does not exist. This kind of confident but false output is commonly called a:", options:["Firewall rule","Backup","Hallucination","Login banner"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Hallucination</strong> is correct because a hallucination is when generative AI produces content that sounds plausible but is fabricated or inaccurate, such as a citation that does not exist.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Firewall rule</b>: a firewall rule controls network traffic and has nothing to do with fabricated AI output.</span><span class='qd'><b>Backup</b>: a backup is a saved copy of data and is unrelated to false AI content.</span><span class='qd'><b>Login banner</b>: a login banner is a notice shown at sign-in and does not describe invented output.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-040", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"Which practice BEST reduces the risk of acting on an AI-generated hallucination?", options:["Assuming anything detailed must be true","Sharing the output immediately without reading it","Turning off spell check","Verifying important claims against a trusted source before relying on them"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Verifying important claims against a trusted source before relying on them</strong> is correct because independent verification catches fabricated or inaccurate details before they cause harm.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Assuming anything detailed must be true</b>: detail does not guarantee accuracy, and hallucinations can be very detailed.</span><span class='qd'><b>Sharing the output immediately without reading it</b>: sharing unread output spreads any errors it contains.</span><span class='qd'><b>Turning off spell check</b>: spell check has no bearing on whether the facts in the output are correct.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-041", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"Why does giving a chatbot more specific detail in your prompt usually improve the result?", options:["Clearer context helps the model predict more relevant, on-target text","It forces the model to access secret databases","It makes the model type faster","It guarantees the answer is 100% correct"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Clearer context helps the model predict more relevant, on-target text</strong> is correct because a detailed prompt narrows what the model should produce, guiding it toward output that matches your actual need.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It forces the model to access secret databases</b>: adding detail does not unlock hidden databases; it just shapes the prediction.</span><span class='qd'><b>It makes the model type faster</b>: prompt detail affects relevance, not typing speed.</span><span class='qd'><b>It guarantees the answer is 100% correct</b>: better prompts improve relevance but cannot guarantee perfect accuracy.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-042", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"hard", q:"An employee asks, \"Does the AI understand my question the way a person does?\" What is the MOST accurate conceptual answer?", options:["Yes, it consciously understands meaning exactly like a human","It processes patterns in language to produce likely responses, without human-style understanding or awareness","It reads your mind directly","It has personal opinions and feelings about your question"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>It processes patterns in language to produce likely responses, without human-style understanding or awareness</strong> is correct because generative AI works by modeling statistical patterns in text rather than possessing genuine comprehension or consciousness.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Yes, it consciously understands meaning exactly like a human</b>: the model has no consciousness and does not understand meaning the way people do.</span><span class='qd'><b>It reads your mind directly</b>: it only responds to the text you provide and cannot access your thoughts.</span><span class='qd'><b>It has personal opinions and feelings about your question</b>: the model has no feelings or personal opinions; it generates text from patterns.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-043", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"hard", q:"A user notices the same prompt can produce slightly different answers each time. Conceptually, this is because generative models often:", options:["Are broken and should be uninstalled","Randomly connect to different servers with different data","Introduce some controlled variation when selecting among likely next words","Copy from a rotating list of fixed responses"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Introduce some controlled variation when selecting among likely next words</strong> is correct because many generative systems allow a degree of variability in word choice, so repeated prompts can yield differently worded but similar responses.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Are broken and should be uninstalled</b>: varying output is expected behavior, not a sign the tool is broken.</span><span class='qd'><b>Randomly connect to different servers with different data</b>: the variation comes from word selection, not from switching to different data servers.</span><span class='qd'><b>Copy from a rotating list of fixed responses</b>: the model generates text rather than cycling through a fixed list of canned replies.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-044", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"easy", q:"Which statement about how generative AI \"knows\" things is MOST accurate for a general audience?", options:["It is connected to a live human expert at all times","It memorized every fact perfectly and never errs","It invents facts on purpose to trick users","It learned patterns from large amounts of text and images during training"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>It learned patterns from large amounts of text and images during training</strong> is correct because generative AI derives its capabilities from patterns absorbed during training on large datasets, which it uses to generate new output.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It is connected to a live human expert at all times</b>: the model generates responses itself and is not staffed by a live expert.</span><span class='qd'><b>It memorized every fact perfectly and never errs</b>: it does not store perfect facts and can make mistakes.</span><span class='qd'><b>It invents facts on purpose to trick users</b>: errors are unintentional byproducts of prediction, not deliberate deception.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-045", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"Which is the BEST reason to treat a generative AI's answer as a starting point rather than a final authority?", options:["Its output can contain errors, so human review adds needed accuracy and judgment","Its output is always wrong and never useful","It cannot produce anything readable","It only works for entertainment and never for work"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Its output can contain errors, so human review adds needed accuracy and judgment</strong> is correct because AI output is useful but fallible, making human review essential before treating it as final.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Its output is always wrong and never useful</b>: AI output is frequently useful, so this overstates the problem.</span><span class='qd'><b>It cannot produce anything readable</b>: generative AI produces readable, coherent text, so this is false.</span><span class='qd'><b>It only works for entertainment and never for work</b>: AI is widely used for real work tasks, not just entertainment.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-046", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"hard", q:"A generative AI assistant is asked about events after its training period and gives outdated information. Conceptually, why does this happen?", options:["The model deleted the recent news to save space","The model reflects what it learned up to a point and may not know very recent events unless given current data","The model is lying to protect a company","The model refuses to discuss anything recent by design"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>The model reflects what it learned up to a point and may not know very recent events unless given current data</strong> is correct because a model's knowledge is bounded by its training, so it can miss recent developments unless supplied with up-to-date information.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The model deleted the recent news to save space</b>: the model never had events past its training and did not delete them.</span><span class='qd'><b>The model is lying to protect a company</b>: outdated answers stem from limited training data, not deliberate deception.</span><span class='qd'><b>The model refuses to discuss anything recent by design</b>: the issue is missing knowledge, not a design choice to refuse recent topics.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-047", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"When a generative AI writes a summary of a document you paste in, it is mainly:", options:["Emailing the document to its developers","Encrypting the document for storage","Producing new condensed wording based on the content you provided","Printing the document automatically"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Producing new condensed wording based on the content you provided</strong> is correct because summarization generates fresh, shorter text that captures the key points of the input you supplied.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Emailing the document to its developers</b>: summarizing does not send your document to developers.</span><span class='qd'><b>Encrypting the document for storage</b>: encryption is a security operation unrelated to writing a summary.</span><span class='qd'><b>Printing the document automatically</b>: producing a summary does not trigger printing.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-048", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"hard", q:"Which explanation BEST helps a non-technical manager understand why AI output quality depends partly on the input?", options:["The model ignores the input entirely","Input length is the only thing that matters, never clarity","Only the time of day affects the answer","Vague or incomplete prompts give the model less to work with, so results may be off-target"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Vague or incomplete prompts give the model less to work with, so results may be off-target</strong> is correct because the model shapes its response around the input, so unclear prompts tend to produce less relevant results.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The model ignores the input entirely</b>: the model relies heavily on the input, so it does not ignore it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Input length is the only thing that matters, never clarity</b>: clarity and relevance matter more than raw length.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only the time of day affects the answer</b>: the time of day does not determine answer quality; the prompt does.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-049", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"A user pastes a long report and asks for \"the three main takeaways.\" What is the model most fundamentally doing to respond?", options:["Generating new text that expresses the key points it identifies in the input","Looking up the report in a public library catalog","Counting the exact number of characters only","Translating the report into machine code"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Generating new text that expresses the key points it identifies in the input</strong> is correct because the model reads the provided content and produces concise, newly worded takeaways from it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Looking up the report in a public library catalog</b>: the model works from the pasted text, not from an external catalog lookup.</span><span class='qd'><b>Counting the exact number of characters only</b>: extracting takeaways is far more than counting characters.</span><span class='qd'><b>Translating the report into machine code</b>: summarizing is not a translation into machine code.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-050", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"easy", q:"Which is the BEST everyday tip for getting more useful results from a generative AI assistant?", options:["Type only a single vague word every time","Tell it clearly what you want, who it's for, and any format you need","Never give it any context","Insist it must be perfect and demand no review"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Tell it clearly what you want, who it's for, and any format you need</strong> is correct because giving purpose, audience, and format helps the model tailor its output to your actual need.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Type only a single vague word every time</b>: a single vague word gives the model too little to produce a useful answer.</span><span class='qd'><b>Never give it any context</b>: withholding context leads to generic, off-target results.</span><span class='qd'><b>Insist it must be perfect and demand no review</b>: skipping review ignores that AI output can contain errors.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-051", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"easy", q:"Which of the following is a well-known AI chat assistant that people use to draft and answer questions in natural language?", options:["A USB flash drive","A paper shredder","ChatGPT","A projector"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>ChatGPT</strong> is correct because ChatGPT is a widely used AI chat assistant that responds to natural-language prompts for tasks like drafting and answering questions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A USB flash drive</b>: a flash drive only stores files and cannot converse or draft text.</span><span class='qd'><b>A paper shredder</b>: a shredder destroys documents and has no AI capabilities.</span><span class='qd'><b>A projector</b>: a projector displays images on a screen and does not answer questions.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-052", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"easy", q:"Google's family of AI models and its assistant are known by which name?", options:["Stapler","Ethernet","Bluetooth","Gemini"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Gemini</strong> is correct because Gemini is the brand name for Google's AI models and assistant used for chat and generative tasks.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Stapler</b>: a stapler is an office tool and not an AI product.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ethernet</b>: Ethernet is a networking standard, not an AI assistant.</span><span class='qd'><b>Bluetooth</b>: Bluetooth is a wireless connection technology and not an AI model.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-053", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"easy", q:"Claude is an AI assistant developed by which company?", options:["Anthropic","A pizza chain","A shoe manufacturer","A lawn-care service"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Anthropic</strong> is correct because Claude is the AI assistant created by Anthropic, used for conversation and generative tasks.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A pizza chain</b>: a pizza chain sells food and does not build AI assistants.</span><span class='qd'><b>A shoe manufacturer</b>: a shoe company makes footwear, not AI models.</span><span class='qd'><b>A lawn-care service</b>: a lawn-care business maintains yards and is unrelated to AI development.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-054", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"easy", q:"Microsoft Copilot is BEST described as:", options:["A physical co-pilot who flies planes","An AI assistant integrated into Microsoft apps to help with tasks like writing and summarizing","A brand of coffee maker","A type of network cable"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>An AI assistant integrated into Microsoft apps to help with tasks like writing and summarizing</strong> is correct because Copilot is Microsoft's AI helper built into products like Word, Excel, and Teams to assist users with everyday tasks.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A physical co-pilot who flies planes</b>: Copilot here is software, not an aircraft crew member.</span><span class='qd'><b>A brand of coffee maker</b>: Copilot is an AI assistant, not a kitchen appliance.</span><span class='qd'><b>A type of network cable</b>: Copilot is software and has nothing to do with cabling.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-055", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"medium", q:"A user wants an AI assistant that is tightly built into Word, Excel, and Outlook to help with documents and email. Which is the MOST natural fit?", options:["A standalone paper planner","A calculator watch","Microsoft Copilot","A fax machine"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Microsoft Copilot</strong> is correct because Copilot is designed to work inside Microsoft 365 apps like Word, Excel, and Outlook, matching the user's need directly.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A standalone paper planner</b>: a paper planner is not software and cannot assist inside Office apps.</span><span class='qd'><b>A calculator watch</b>: a calculator watch does math and cannot help with documents or email.</span><span class='qd'><b>A fax machine</b>: a fax machine transmits paper images and offers no AI assistance in apps.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-056", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"medium", q:"Which statement about mainstream AI assistants (ChatGPT, Gemini, Claude, Copilot) is MOST accurate?", options:["They are all identical and made by the same company","Only one of them can process text","None of them can accept typed prompts","They can each help with tasks like drafting, summarizing, and answering questions in natural language"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>They can each help with tasks like drafting, summarizing, and answering questions in natural language</strong> is correct because these popular assistants share broad capabilities such as drafting text, summarizing, and answering questions, even though they differ in details.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>They are all identical and made by the same company</b>: they are made by different companies and differ in features, so they are not identical.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only one of them can process text</b>: all of these assistants process text prompts, not just one.</span><span class='qd'><b>None of them can accept typed prompts</b>: accepting typed prompts is a core function of every one of them.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-057", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"medium", q:"A colleague asks which company makes ChatGPT. What is the correct answer?", options:["OpenAI","Anthropic","Google","A car manufacturer"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>OpenAI</strong> is correct because ChatGPT is developed by OpenAI, the organization behind the GPT family of models.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Anthropic</b>: Anthropic develops Claude, not ChatGPT.</span><span class='qd'><b>Google</b>: Google develops Gemini, not ChatGPT.</span><span class='qd'><b>A car manufacturer</b>: an automaker does not produce ChatGPT.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-058", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"hard", q:"An organization already uses Google Workspace heavily and wants an AI assistant that fits naturally with Gmail, Docs, and Drive. Which choice aligns BEST with that ecosystem?", options:["Microsoft Copilot inside Excel only","Gemini","A typewriter","An overhead projector"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Gemini</strong> is correct because Gemini is Google's assistant and integrates naturally with Google Workspace tools like Gmail, Docs, and Drive.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Microsoft Copilot inside Excel only</b>: Copilot is tied to Microsoft apps, so it does not fit the Google Workspace ecosystem as naturally.</span><span class='qd'><b>A typewriter</b>: a typewriter is a mechanical device with no AI or cloud integration.</span><span class='qd'><b>An overhead projector</b>: a projector displays slides and cannot act as an AI assistant.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-059", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"hard", q:"A team is comparing AI assistants and wants a realistic expectation. Which statement is MOST accurate?", options:["All assistants are exactly the same, so the choice never matters","The most expensive assistant is always the best for every task","Different assistants have different strengths, interfaces, and integrations, so the best choice depends on the task and existing tools","Only assistants that require coding are worth using"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Different assistants have different strengths, interfaces, and integrations, so the best choice depends on the task and existing tools</strong> is correct because assistants vary in features and ecosystem fit, so the right pick depends on the specific need and the tools already in use.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>All assistants are exactly the same, so the choice never matters</b>: they differ in capabilities and integrations, so the choice does matter.</span><span class='qd'><b>The most expensive assistant is always the best for every task</b>: price does not guarantee the best fit for a given task.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only assistants that require coding are worth using</b>: most leading assistants require no coding and are highly useful.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-060", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"medium", q:"Which pairing of AI assistant to its developer is CORRECT?", options:["Gemini — OpenAI","ChatGPT — Google","Copilot — Anthropic","Claude — Anthropic"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Claude — Anthropic</strong> is correct because Anthropic is the company that develops the Claude assistant.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Gemini — OpenAI</b>: Gemini is developed by Google, not OpenAI.</span><span class='qd'><b>ChatGPT — Google</b>: ChatGPT is developed by OpenAI, not Google.</span><span class='qd'><b>Copilot — Anthropic</b>: Copilot is a Microsoft product, not an Anthropic one.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-061", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"easy", q:"Many AI assistants are accessed through a simple interface where you:", options:["Type a message and read the assistant's reply, like a chat conversation","Solder wires together to send a request","Mail a physical letter to the assistant","Fill out a paper form and fax it"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Type a message and read the assistant's reply, like a chat conversation</strong> is correct because most modern AI assistants use a chat-style interface where you type prompts and receive text responses.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Solder wires together to send a request</b>: using an assistant requires no hardware assembly.</span><span class='qd'><b>Mail a physical letter to the assistant</b>: interaction is digital and instant, not by postal mail.</span><span class='qd'><b>Fill out a paper form and fax it</b>: assistants respond through software, not by fax.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-062", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"medium", q:"A user says, \"I want an AI I can chat with to brainstorm ideas and get thoughtful written responses.\" Which category of tool are they describing?", options:["A spreadsheet macro","A general-purpose AI chat assistant such as Claude, ChatGPT, or Gemini","A barcode scanner","A screen recorder"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>A general-purpose AI chat assistant such as Claude, ChatGPT, or Gemini</strong> is correct because brainstorming and getting thoughtful written replies through conversation is exactly what general-purpose chat assistants are built for.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A spreadsheet macro</b>: a macro automates spreadsheet steps and cannot brainstorm in natural language.</span><span class='qd'><b>A barcode scanner</b>: a scanner reads codes and offers no conversational help.</span><span class='qd'><b>A screen recorder</b>: a screen recorder captures video and does not generate ideas.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-063", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"hard", q:"A cautious manager asks whether popular AI assistants can be trusted to always give correct answers. Which response is MOST accurate?", options:["Yes, the well-known ones are always correct","Only paid assistants can ever be wrong","No single assistant is guaranteed correct; all can make mistakes, so verify important outputs","Assistants never produce factual errors of any kind"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>No single assistant is guaranteed correct; all can make mistakes, so verify important outputs</strong> is correct because every mainstream assistant can produce errors or hallucinations, so users should verify important information regardless of the tool.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Yes, the well-known ones are always correct</b>: even well-known assistants can be wrong, so this is false.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only paid assistants can ever be wrong</b>: both free and paid assistants can make mistakes.</span><span class='qd'><b>Assistants never produce factual errors of any kind</b>: assistants do sometimes produce factual errors, so this is incorrect.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-064", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"medium", q:"Which of these is TRUE about how these assistants are commonly offered to users?", options:["They are all completely free with no paid options ever","They can only be bought as physical boxed software","They require a mainframe computer at home","Many offer free tiers plus paid plans with additional features or higher limits"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Many offer free tiers plus paid plans with additional features or higher limits</strong> is correct because leading assistants commonly provide a free level of access alongside paid plans that unlock more capabilities or higher usage.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>They are all completely free with no paid options ever</b>: most have paid tiers, so this is inaccurate.</span><span class='qd'><b>They can only be bought as physical boxed software</b>: they are cloud services accessed online, not boxed software.</span><span class='qd'><b>They require a mainframe computer at home</b>: they run in the cloud and work from ordinary devices.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-065", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"hard", q:"An office wants one clear guideline for choosing among ChatGPT, Gemini, Claude, and Copilot. Which guideline is MOST practical?", options:["Pick based on which tools you already use, the features you need, and your organization's data policies","Always pick the newest one released regardless of fit","Choose whichever has the shortest name","Select at random since they are interchangeable in every way"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Pick based on which tools you already use, the features you need, and your organization's data policies</strong> is correct because matching an assistant to your existing tools, requirements, and governance rules yields the most practical and safe choice.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Always pick the newest one released regardless of fit</b>: newness alone does not ensure the best fit for your needs.</span><span class='qd'><b>Choose whichever has the shortest name</b>: a name's length has no bearing on suitability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Select at random since they are interchangeable in every way</b>: they differ meaningfully, so random selection ignores real trade-offs.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-066", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"medium", q:"Which best describes a shared capability of ChatGPT, Gemini, and Claude?", options:["They can physically repair hardware","They can generate and revise written text based on conversational prompts","They only work without any internet connection ever","They are limited to displaying static images"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>They can generate and revise written text based on conversational prompts</strong> is correct because generating and refining text from prompts is a core shared strength of these general-purpose assistants.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>They can physically repair hardware</b>: these are software assistants and cannot perform physical repairs.</span><span class='qd'><b>They only work without any internet connection ever</b>: these cloud assistants generally require internet access.</span><span class='qd'><b>They are limited to displaying static images</b>: they primarily work with language and are not limited to static images.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-067", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"easy", q:"If a teammate mentions using \"Copilot in Excel\" to help build a formula, they are using:", options:["A separate physical robot at their desk","A printed manual","An AI assistant feature embedded in the app","A spreadsheet from the 1990s with no AI"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>An AI assistant feature embedded in the app</strong> is correct because Copilot in Excel is an AI feature built directly into the application to assist with tasks like creating formulas.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A separate physical robot at their desk</b>: Copilot is software inside the app, not a physical robot.</span><span class='qd'><b>A printed manual</b>: a manual is static reference material, not an interactive AI feature.</span><span class='qd'><b>A spreadsheet from the 1990s with no AI</b>: an old spreadsheet without AI cannot provide Copilot's assistance.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-068", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"hard", q:"A company handling sensitive client data is choosing an AI assistant. Beyond features, which consideration is MOST important?", options:["Which assistant has the most colorful logo","Whether the assistant's name is easy to spell","How many emojis the assistant can display","How the assistant handles data privacy and whether it meets the organization's security requirements"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>How the assistant handles data privacy and whether it meets the organization's security requirements</strong> is correct because when sensitive data is involved, data handling, privacy, and security compliance are decisive factors in choosing a tool.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Which assistant has the most colorful logo</b>: a logo's appearance has no impact on data protection.</span><span class='qd'><b>Whether the assistant's name is easy to spell</b>: spelling ease is irrelevant to security and privacy.</span><span class='qd'><b>How many emojis the assistant can display</b>: emoji support does not affect handling of sensitive data.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-069", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"medium", q:"Which statement about the pace of AI assistants is MOST accurate for a general user?", options:["These tools update frequently, so features and model versions can change over time","Once released, they never change or improve","They are frozen and identical to their first version forever","They lose all features every month"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>These tools update frequently, so features and model versions can change over time</strong> is correct because AI assistants are actively developed, and their capabilities and underlying models are updated regularly.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Once released, they never change or improve</b>: these tools are updated often, so they do change.</span><span class='qd'><b>They are frozen and identical to their first version forever</b>: ongoing updates mean they are not frozen at their first version.</span><span class='qd'><b>They lose all features every month</b>: updates generally add or refine features rather than removing everything monthly.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-070", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"medium", q:"A user asks whether they can use more than one AI assistant. What is the BEST answer?", options:["No, using more than one is technically impossible","Yes, people often use different assistants for different tasks or preferences","Only if all assistants come from the same company","Only developers are allowed to use multiple assistants"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Yes, people often use different assistants for different tasks or preferences</strong> is correct because there is no barrier to using multiple assistants, and many people choose whichever suits a given task best.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>No, using more than one is technically impossible</b>: using several assistants is entirely possible and common.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only if all assistants come from the same company</b>: assistants from different companies can all be used.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only developers are allowed to use multiple assistants</b>: anyone can use multiple assistants, not just developers.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-071", domain:1, obj:"1.5", diff:"easy", q:"What is a key difference between generative AI and a traditional web search engine?", options:["Search composes original essays, while AI only returns links","They are exactly the same tool","Generative AI composes a new answer, while search returns a list of existing web links","Generative AI can only return blue links"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Generative AI composes a new answer, while search returns a list of existing web links</strong> is correct because search engines point you to existing pages, whereas generative AI produces a synthesized response in its own words.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Search composes original essays, while AI only returns links</b>: this reverses their roles; search returns links and AI composes text.</span><span class='qd'><b>They are exactly the same tool</b>: they work differently, so they are not the same.</span><span class='qd'><b>Generative AI can only return blue links</b>: returning link lists describes search, not generative AI.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-072", domain:1, obj:"1.5", diff:"easy", q:"How does traditional software (like a calculator app) differ from generative AI?", options:["Traditional software learns new behavior on its own each day","Generative AI can only add and subtract numbers","They both always produce identical output for any input","Traditional software follows fixed programmed rules, while generative AI produces flexible output from learned patterns"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Traditional software follows fixed programmed rules, while generative AI produces flexible output from learned patterns</strong> is correct because conventional programs execute predefined logic, whereas generative AI generates varied output based on patterns it learned.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Traditional software learns new behavior on its own each day</b>: traditional software does not learn by itself; it follows fixed rules.</span><span class='qd'><b>Generative AI can only add and subtract numbers</b>: generative AI creates rich content and is not limited to arithmetic.</span><span class='qd'><b>They both always produce identical output for any input</b>: generative AI can vary its output, unlike deterministic traditional software.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-073", domain:1, obj:"1.5", diff:"medium", q:"A user wants the most current, source-linked information about today's news. Which tool is generally the BEST fit?", options:["A web search engine that returns up-to-date sources","A generative AI with a fixed training cutoff and no live browsing","A calculator app","A drawing program"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>A web search engine that returns up-to-date sources</strong> is correct because search engines index current web content and link to sources, making them well suited for breaking news.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A generative AI with a fixed training cutoff and no live browsing</b>: a model without live access may not know today's events, so it is a poor fit for breaking news.</span><span class='qd'><b>A calculator app</b>: a calculator performs math and cannot retrieve news.</span><span class='qd'><b>A drawing program</b>: a drawing app creates graphics and does not provide news sources.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-074", domain:1, obj:"1.5", diff:"medium", q:"Which scenario is a BETTER fit for generative AI than for a traditional search engine?", options:["Finding the official government website for passport renewal","Rewriting a rough paragraph into a polished, friendlier tone","Getting a list of nearby restaurants with reviews","Locating today's live sports scores"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Rewriting a rough paragraph into a polished, friendlier tone</strong> is correct because transforming and generating text is a strength of generative AI, whereas the other tasks are better served by search that locates existing pages or live data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Finding the official government website for passport renewal</b>: locating a specific authoritative site is a search task.</span><span class='qd'><b>Getting a list of nearby restaurants with reviews</b>: finding local listings and reviews is what search and maps do best.</span><span class='qd'><b>Locating today's live sports scores</b>: live scores require current data retrieval, which favors search.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-075", domain:1, obj:"1.5", diff:"medium", q:"Which statement about traditional software versus AI is MOST accurate?", options:["AI is always more reliable than traditional software for exact calculations","Traditional software can write creative stories better than AI","Traditional software gives predictable results from fixed logic; AI can handle ambiguity but may be less predictable","AI cannot handle any uncertain or open-ended requests"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Traditional software gives predictable results from fixed logic; AI can handle ambiguity but may be less predictable</strong> is correct because deterministic programs return consistent results, while AI is better with open-ended input yet can vary and err.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>AI is always more reliable than traditional software for exact calculations</b>: deterministic software is more reliable for exact math than a language model.</span><span class='qd'><b>Traditional software can write creative stories better than AI</b>: creative writing is a strength of generative AI, not fixed-rule software.</span><span class='qd'><b>AI cannot handle any uncertain or open-ended requests</b>: handling open-ended requests is precisely where AI shines.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-076", domain:1, obj:"1.5", diff:"hard", q:"A researcher needs both a synthesized explanation and verifiable citations. What is the MOST sensible approach?", options:["Rely solely on generative AI and never check any source","Use only a calculator to gather citations","Assume the AI's cited sources are always real without checking","Use generative AI for a draft explanation, then use search to confirm facts and find citations"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Use generative AI for a draft explanation, then use search to confirm facts and find citations</strong> is correct because combining AI's drafting speed with search-based verification produces an explanation that is both clear and grounded in real sources.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Rely solely on generative AI and never check any source</b>: skipping verification risks including fabricated or wrong claims.</span><span class='qd'><b>Use only a calculator to gather citations</b>: a calculator cannot find or verify citations.</span><span class='qd'><b>Assume the AI's cited sources are always real without checking</b>: AI can fabricate citations, so assuming they are real is unsafe.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-077", domain:1, obj:"1.5", diff:"hard", q:"Why might a generative AI answer feel more \"complete\" than a search result, yet still be risky to trust?", options:["It presents a confident, unified narrative that can hide gaps or errors, unlike a list of sources you can inspect","It always cites peer-reviewed studies for every sentence","It is incapable of ever being wrong","It only summarizes government data"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>It presents a confident, unified narrative that can hide gaps or errors, unlike a list of sources you can inspect</strong> is correct because a smooth, self-contained answer can mask inaccuracies, whereas a list of search sources lets you evaluate each one.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It always cites peer-reviewed studies for every sentence</b>: generative AI does not reliably cite peer-reviewed studies for every claim.</span><span class='qd'><b>It is incapable of ever being wrong</b>: generative AI can be wrong, which is exactly why its polish is risky.</span><span class='qd'><b>It only summarizes government data</b>: it draws on broad training data, not solely government sources.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-078", domain:1, obj:"1.5", diff:"medium", q:"Which task is BEST handled by traditional, rule-based software rather than generative AI?", options:["Brainstorming creative slogans for a campaign","Calculating exact payroll totals that must be identical every time","Rewriting an email in a warmer tone","Suggesting several possible titles for an article"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Calculating exact payroll totals that must be identical every time</strong> is correct because precise, repeatable arithmetic is a job for deterministic software, not for generative AI that may vary its output.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Brainstorming creative slogans for a campaign</b>: brainstorming varied ideas is a strength of generative AI.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rewriting an email in a warmer tone</b>: tone rewriting is a natural generative AI task.</span><span class='qd'><b>Suggesting several possible titles for an article</b>: generating multiple creative options suits generative AI well.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-079", domain:1, obj:"1.5", diff:"hard", q:"An employee argues, \"We should replace our search tools entirely with a generative AI assistant.\" Which is the MOST balanced response?", options:["Yes, generative AI fully replaces the need for search in every case","No, generative AI is useless and should be avoided","Each tool has different strengths; generative AI drafts and explains, while search finds and verifies current sources, so both are valuable","Search should be replaced only because AI is newer"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Each tool has different strengths; generative AI drafts and explains, while search finds and verifies current sources, so both are valuable</strong> is correct because generative AI and search serve complementary purposes, so keeping both provides the best coverage.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Yes, generative AI fully replaces the need for search in every case</b>: AI does not reliably provide current, verifiable sources, so it cannot fully replace search.</span><span class='qd'><b>No, generative AI is useless and should be avoided</b>: generative AI is genuinely useful, so dismissing it is unbalanced.</span><span class='qd'><b>Search should be replaced only because AI is newer</b>: being newer is not a sound reason to abandon a still-useful tool.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-080", domain:1, obj:"1.5", diff:"easy", q:"A key reason to double-check a generative AI's factual claims, compared to a normal search, is that:", options:["The AI always links every claim to a trusted encyclopedia","Search never returns any sources","The AI cannot produce any factual statements","The AI may state something incorrect without showing you a source to verify"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>The AI may state something incorrect without showing you a source to verify</strong> is correct because generative AI often presents claims without citations, so you cannot easily confirm them the way you can with search results.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The AI always links every claim to a trusted encyclopedia</b>: generative AI does not reliably link each claim to a source.</span><span class='qd'><b>Search never returns any sources</b>: search is specifically designed to return sources.</span><span class='qd'><b>The AI cannot produce any factual statements</b>: AI does produce factual statements, which is why verifying them matters.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-081", domain:1, obj:"1.5", diff:"medium", q:"Which best captures how generative AI differs from a database query?", options:["A database returns exact stored records, while generative AI produces new text that may not be an exact record","Both return only exact stored records","A database invents new records each time","Generative AI can only return numbers from a table"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>A database returns exact stored records, while generative AI produces new text that may not be an exact record</strong> is correct because a database retrieves precise stored data, whereas generative AI creates new output that is not a guaranteed exact record.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Both return only exact stored records</b>: generative AI does not return exact stored records; it generates text.</span><span class='qd'><b>A database invents new records each time</b>: a database returns stored data and does not invent records.</span><span class='qd'><b>Generative AI can only return numbers from a table</b>: generative AI produces varied content, not just table numbers.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-082", domain:1, obj:"1.5", diff:"hard", q:"A team wants to decide, for each task, whether to use search or generative AI. Which decision rule is MOST sound?", options:["Always use generative AI because it is newer","Use search when you need current, verifiable sources; use generative AI when you need drafting, summarizing, or idea generation","Always use search because AI is never helpful","Flip a coin since the tools are identical"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Use search when you need current, verifiable sources; use generative AI when you need drafting, summarizing, or idea generation</strong> is correct because matching each tool to its strength gives the most reliable results across different needs.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Always use generative AI because it is newer</b>: newness does not make AI the right tool for every task.</span><span class='qd'><b>Always use search because AI is never helpful</b>: AI is helpful for many tasks, so this rule wastes its strengths.</span><span class='qd'><b>Flip a coin since the tools are identical</b>: the tools are not identical, so random choice ignores real differences.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-083", domain:1, obj:"1.5", diff:"medium", q:"Which is an accurate way to describe the \"output\" difference between search and generative AI?", options:["Both refuse to provide any output","Search generates original paragraphs; AI only lists links","Search points you to information; generative AI generates information for you","Neither can respond to a typed query"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Search points you to information; generative AI generates information for you</strong> is correct because search directs you to existing sources, while generative AI creates a response directly.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Both refuse to provide any output</b>: both tools clearly provide output, just of different kinds.</span><span class='qd'><b>Search generates original paragraphs; AI only lists links</b>: this reverses their behavior, since AI generates text and search lists links.</span><span class='qd'><b>Neither can respond to a typed query</b>: both respond to typed queries.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-084", domain:1, obj:"1.5", diff:"hard", q:"A manager notes that traditional software \"does exactly what it was programmed to do.\" Why is this both a strength and a limitation compared to AI?", options:["It means traditional software is always smarter than AI","It means traditional software learns on its own, unlike AI","It means traditional software can never be trusted","It is reliable and predictable, but it cannot flexibly handle new or ambiguous situations the way AI can"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>It is reliable and predictable, but it cannot flexibly handle new or ambiguous situations the way AI can</strong> is correct because fixed programming ensures consistency yet limits adaptability, which is where AI's flexibility becomes valuable.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It means traditional software is always smarter than AI</b>: following fixed rules is not the same as being smarter; each has different strengths.</span><span class='qd'><b>It means traditional software learns on its own, unlike AI</b>: traditional software does not learn on its own; AI is the one that learns from data.</span><span class='qd'><b>It means traditional software can never be trusted</b>: predictable software is often highly trustworthy for its intended tasks.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-085", domain:1, obj:"1.5", diff:"medium", q:"When would a simple traditional program be preferable to generative AI?", options:["When a task needs exact, consistent, rule-based results every time","When a task requires open-ended creative writing","When you want varied phrasing on each run","When you need brainstorming with many options"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>When a task needs exact, consistent, rule-based results every time</strong> is correct because deterministic programs guarantee the same correct result repeatedly, which generative AI does not promise.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>When a task requires open-ended creative writing</b>: creative writing favors generative AI, not fixed-rule software.</span><span class='qd'><b>When you want varied phrasing on each run</b>: wanting variety points to generative AI, not deterministic software.</span><span class='qd'><b>When you need brainstorming with many options</b>: brainstorming many options is a generative AI strength.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-086", domain:1, obj:"1.5", diff:"easy", q:"Compared with typing keywords into a search box, interacting with a generative AI assistant usually feels more like:", options:["Filling out a numeric spreadsheet","Having a natural-language conversation","Soldering a circuit board","Rewinding a cassette tape"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Having a natural-language conversation</strong> is correct because generative AI assistants respond to full sentences and follow-up questions, making the interaction feel conversational rather than keyword-based.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Filling out a numeric spreadsheet</b>: chatting with an assistant is language-based, not entering numbers in cells.</span><span class='qd'><b>Soldering a circuit board</b>: using an assistant is a software interaction, not a hardware task.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rewinding a cassette tape</b>: a cassette is unrelated to conversing with an AI.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-087", domain:1, obj:"1.5", diff:"hard", q:"A user got a plausible-looking statistic from a generative AI and a set of source links from a search engine on the same topic. Which action reflects the BEST information hygiene?", options:["Publish the AI statistic immediately because it looked specific","Ignore the search sources entirely","Trace the statistic to a credible source before using it, using the search results to verify","Assume the search links are wrong and trust only the AI"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Trace the statistic to a credible source before using it, using the search results to verify</strong> is correct because verifying a specific claim against credible sources protects against acting on an AI hallucination.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Publish the AI statistic immediately because it looked specific</b>: specificity does not confirm accuracy, so publishing unverified is risky.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignore the search sources entirely</b>: ignoring the verifiable sources discards the best way to check the claim.</span><span class='qd'><b>Assume the search links are wrong and trust only the AI</b>: dismissing sources in favor of unverified AI output is poor information hygiene.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-088", domain:1, obj:"1.5", diff:"medium", q:"Which statement about generative AI and traditional search working together is MOST accurate?", options:["They can never be used on the same task","Using both always produces worse results than using one","They are the same product with two names","They can complement each other: AI drafts and explains, search verifies and finds current sources"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>They can complement each other: AI drafts and explains, search verifies and finds current sources</strong> is correct because pairing generative AI's drafting with search's sourcing produces stronger, better-verified results.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>They can never be used on the same task</b>: they are frequently combined on the same task to good effect.</span><span class='qd'><b>Using both always produces worse results than using one</b>: combining them typically improves results rather than harming them.</span><span class='qd'><b>They are the same product with two names</b>: they are distinct tools that work differently.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-089", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"medium", q:"Which of the following BEST describes \"training data\" for an AI model in plain terms?", options:["The examples the model learned from to recognize patterns","The electricity bill for running the computer","The color scheme of the app","The name of the company that sells the model"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>The examples the model learned from to recognize patterns</strong> is correct because training data is the collection of examples an AI model studies to learn the patterns it later uses to produce output.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The electricity bill for running the computer</b>: energy costs are unrelated to what the model learns from.</span><span class='qd'><b>The color scheme of the app</b>: the interface colors have nothing to do with training data.</span><span class='qd'><b>The name of the company that sells the model</b>: a vendor's name is not the data used to train the model.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-090", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"hard", q:"A manager asks why two AI models can give different answers to the same question. Which explanation is MOST accurate for a general audience?", options:["One model is always right and the other is always wrong","They were trained on different data and designed differently, so their outputs can vary","They must be identical, so any difference is impossible","The difference depends only on the user's typing speed"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>They were trained on different data and designed differently, so their outputs can vary</strong> is correct because models differ in training data and design, which naturally leads to different responses to the same prompt.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>One model is always right and the other is always wrong</b>: neither model is guaranteed always right or always wrong.</span><span class='qd'><b>They must be identical, so any difference is impossible</b>: models are not identical, so differences are expected.</span><span class='qd'><b>The difference depends only on the user's typing speed</b>: typing speed does not determine which answer a model gives.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-091", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"medium", q:"A user wants a generative AI to answer in a specific format, such as a bulleted list. What is the MOST effective way to get that?", options:["Assume the model will always guess the right format","Type in all capital letters to force formatting","Clearly ask for the desired format in the prompt","Send the request twice with no instructions"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Clearly ask for the desired format in the prompt</strong> is correct because stating the format you want, such as a bulleted list, guides the model to structure its response accordingly.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Assume the model will always guess the right format</b>: without guidance the model may not choose the format you want.</span><span class='qd'><b>Type in all capital letters to force formatting</b>: capitalization does not control output formatting.</span><span class='qd'><b>Send the request twice with no instructions</b>: repeating a request without format instructions does not ensure the desired structure.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-092", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"medium", q:"A user relies on an AI assistant for a quick fact and wants to reduce the chance of being misled. Which habit is MOST helpful?", options:["Believe the first answer because it appeared instantly","Only trust answers that are very long","Avoid rephrasing the question ever","Cross-check important facts with a reliable source"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Cross-check important facts with a reliable source</strong> is correct because verifying key facts against a trusted source guards against AI errors and hallucinations.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Believe the first answer because it appeared instantly</b>: speed of response says nothing about accuracy.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only trust answers that are very long</b>: length does not indicate correctness.</span><span class='qd'><b>Avoid rephrasing the question ever</b>: rephrasing can actually help clarify and improve an answer, so avoiding it is not helpful.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-093", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"medium", q:"A team lead wants to introduce AI tools responsibly. Which first move is MOST appropriate?", options:["Set simple guidelines on what data can and cannot be shared with AI tools","Encourage staff to paste any confidential data into any AI tool","Ban all discussion of AI without explanation","Require everyone to memorize how models are built"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>Set simple guidelines on what data can and cannot be shared with AI tools</strong> is correct because clear data-sharing guidelines let staff use AI productively while protecting sensitive information.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Encourage staff to paste any confidential data into any AI tool</b>: pasting confidential data into unapproved tools risks serious data exposure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ban all discussion of AI without explanation</b>: an unexplained ban blocks useful adoption and does not address responsible use.</span><span class='qd'><b>Require everyone to memorize how models are built</b>: technical model internals are not necessary for responsible everyday use.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-094", domain:1, obj:"1.5", diff:"hard", q:"Which scenario shows the CLEAREST advantage of generative AI over both traditional software and search?", options:["Computing the exact square root of a number","Turning messy meeting notes into a clear, well-structured summary in seconds","Retrieving the official URL of a government agency","Listing the ten newest news headlines with links"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>Turning messy meeting notes into a clear, well-structured summary in seconds</strong> is correct because transforming unstructured text into a coherent summary is a distinctive strength of generative AI that fixed-rule software and link-based search do not provide.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Computing the exact square root of a number</b>: exact calculation is best handled by deterministic software.</span><span class='qd'><b>Retrieving the official URL of a government agency</b>: finding a specific official site is a search task.</span><span class='qd'><b>Listing the ten newest news headlines with links</b>: current headlines with links are best gathered through search.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-095", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"easy", q:"Which phrase BEST completes this sentence: \"Generative AI is a type of ___ that creates new content.\"", options:["Printer","Spreadsheet","Artificial intelligence","Web browser"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Artificial intelligence</strong> is correct because generative AI is a category within artificial intelligence that focuses on producing new content.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Printer</b>: a printer is a hardware device, not a category of AI.</span><span class='qd'><b>Spreadsheet</b>: a spreadsheet is a productivity tool, not the field that generative AI belongs to.</span><span class='qd'><b>Web browser</b>: a browser displays web pages and is not the parent category of generative AI.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-096", domain:1, obj:"1.3", diff:"hard", q:"A user is surprised that a generative AI gave a detailed answer to a question about a topic it clearly cannot know precisely. What is the BEST explanation?", options:["The model secretly contacted an expert for the answer","The model is guaranteed accurate whenever it sounds detailed","The model refuses to answer unknown topics, so the answer must be true","The model generated plausible-sounding text, which can include confident but unverified or invented details"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>The model generated plausible-sounding text, which can include confident but unverified or invented details</strong> is correct because generative AI produces fluent output that can appear authoritative even when parts are fabricated, which is why verification matters.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The model secretly contacted an expert for the answer</b>: the model generates text itself and does not consult a live expert.</span><span class='qd'><b>The model is guaranteed accurate whenever it sounds detailed</b>: detail does not guarantee accuracy, as hallucinations can be detailed.</span><span class='qd'><b>The model refuses to answer unknown topics, so the answer must be true</b>: the model often answers even uncertain topics, so an answer is not proof of truth.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-097", domain:1, obj:"1.4", diff:"easy", q:"Which of the following is NOT one of the widely known general-purpose AI assistants?", options:["A standard desktop calculator","ChatGPT","Gemini","Claude"], answer:0, explain:"<strong>A standard desktop calculator</strong> is correct because a calculator is basic arithmetic software and is not an AI chat assistant, unlike ChatGPT, Gemini, and Claude.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>ChatGPT</b>: ChatGPT is a well-known general-purpose AI assistant, so it does not fit \"not one of them.\"</span><span class='qd'><b>Gemini</b>: Gemini is Google's recognized AI assistant, so it belongs on the list.</span><span class='qd'><b>Claude</b>: Claude is Anthropic's well-known AI assistant, so it is one of them.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-098", domain:1, obj:"1.5", diff:"medium", q:"A user needs to know whether a store is open right now. Why is a generative AI with no live data a POOR choice here?", options:["It will always call the store to confirm","It may not have current hours and could give outdated or made-up information","It refuses to answer any location questions","It only works for math problems"], answer:1, explain:"<strong>It may not have current hours and could give outdated or made-up information</strong> is correct because a model without live access cannot reliably know present-moment details like current store hours and may produce stale or invented answers.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It will always call the store to confirm</b>: the model does not place phone calls to verify information.</span><span class='qd'><b>It refuses to answer any location questions</b>: it will often attempt an answer, which is exactly the risk here.</span><span class='qd'><b>It only works for math problems</b>: generative AI handles many tasks beyond math, so this is false.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-099", domain:1, obj:"1.2", diff:"medium", q:"Which of the following BEST distinguishes generative AI from other machine learning that only classifies or predicts?", options:["Generative AI can only sort emails","Classifiers create brand-new images from scratch","Generative AI creates new content, while classifiers label or forecast from existing data","There is no difference between them"], answer:2, explain:"<strong>Generative AI creates new content, while classifiers label or forecast from existing data</strong> is correct because the defining feature of generative AI is producing new output, whereas classification and prediction models assign labels or forecast values.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Generative AI can only sort emails</b>: sorting emails is a classification task, not the defining generative capability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Classifiers create brand-new images from scratch</b>: creating new images is generative AI, not classification.</span><span class='qd'><b>There is no difference between them</b>: generating content versus labeling data is a real and important difference.</span>" },
{ id:"D1-100", domain:1, obj:"1.1", diff:"hard", q:"An executive summarizes AI adoption as \"a tool that augments people, not a magic replacement for judgment.\" Which everyday practice BEST reflects that mindset?", options:["Letting AI make all final decisions to remove human involvement","Trusting AI output without any checks to save time","Avoiding AI entirely so no judgment is ever needed","Using AI to speed up drafts while people review, decide, and stay accountable"], answer:3, explain:"<strong>Using AI to speed up drafts while people review, decide, and stay accountable</strong> is correct because it treats AI as an aid that boosts productivity while humans keep responsibility for decisions, matching the augment-not-replace mindset.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Letting AI make all final decisions to remove human involvement</b>: removing human involvement contradicts using AI to augment rather than replace judgment.</span><span class='qd'><b>Trusting AI output without any checks to save time</b>: skipping checks abandons the human oversight the mindset requires.</span><span class='qd'><b>Avoiding AI entirely so no judgment is ever needed</b>: avoiding AI forfeits its benefits and misreads the augment-people philosophy.</span>" }
);
